observations.recommendation:
We recommended to the management to:
Require every office to submit the report of Fuel Consumption pertaining to CY 2024 and to submit the subject report on a monthly basis thereafter, duly supported with adequate and duly filled up documents;
Require the City Accounting Office to make a reconciliation and identify the cause of the variance of the fuel inventory amounting to P21.661Million so that adjustments can be made accordingly;
Require the City Accounting Office to make the necessary adjustment to correct prior year expenses recorded in the current year; and
Require the City Accounting Office to submit the appropriate documents to support JEV No. 2024-12-023802.

We recommended to the management to:
Expedite the investigation of PPE items not located/found, non-existent, unserviceable, damaged and missing in the RPCPPE and follow the disposition procedures prescribed in Sections 7 and 8 of COA Circular No. 2020-006;
Instruct the Inventory Committee to follow the prescribed format of the RPCPPE.;
Instruct the Inventory Committee to finalize the one-time cleansing and submit the Inventory Count Form, List of PPEs Found at Station and List of Non/Existing and Missing PPEs;
Include in the annual physical count the Work/Zoo Animals and the CIP accounts to establish their existence and the correctness of the reported balances, to finalize and submit all remaining RPCPPEs conducted for CY 2024; and
Require the City Financial Accounting Services Division of the City Accounting Office to ensure that depreciation expense is recognized to all depreciable assets, and ensure the reclassification of PPE items costing below 50K to the appropriate accounts.

We recommended to the Local Chief Executive the following:
To require the Accounting Office, City Engineering Office, the CGSO and the Inventory Committee to gather the data and information relating to the non-existing, damaged road network properties for proper derecognition; identify/trace the location of the road networks not found during the conduct of physical count; and coordinate in assessing the value of the road lot component and for its subsequent recording in the books of account;
Require City Engineering Office and the CGSO to furnish the audit team a copy of the road map;
Require the CGSO to keep and maintain Property Card for Local Road Network and to use the prescribed format of the Report on the Physical Count of Local Road Network; and
Instruct the accounting Office to disclose the road network in the Notes to FS following the presentation prescribed by the existing circular.

We recommended to the City Mayor to instruct the City Accounting Office to:
Strictly ensure compliance with IPSAS 23 in relation to the recognition of revenue from non- exchange transactions, specifically on the fund transfers, taking into consideration the terms and conditions in the MOA and ensure that revenue is recognized equivalent to the liability reduced in view of the fulfillment of conditions relative to the funds recorded in the Trust Fund;
Implement or improve procedures for tracking and confirming the fulfillment of conditions related to trust funds and grants to ensure that similar issues don’t arise in future financial periods;
Promptly transfer all completed projects from the Trust Fund to the General Fund to ensure that depreciation expense is recognized in the proper books; and
Promptly transfer the net revenue arising from interest on bank to the General Fund for proper recognition of income.

We recommended to the management to:
Direct the LDRRMC, thru the LDRRM Office, to prepare the LDRRMFIP/LDRRMP in accordance with the prescribed format, and annually prepare the LDRRMFIP/LDRRMP for the Regular Annual Budget;
Instruct the City Accounting and Budget Offices to identify the causes of the discrepancy aggregating P11,871,583.24 and submit the said reconciliation to the audit team;
Instruct the City Accounting Office to reconcile the discrepancy amounting P28,434,439.48 between the Special Trust Fund balance in the Report on Sources and Utilization of DRRMF with the TL- DRRMF account and make the necessary adjustments and corrections in the respective records/reports and submit to the audit team;
Require the concerned offices to scrutinize the Report on Sources and Utilization of DRRM Fund and require periodic and timely reconciliation with accounting and budget records to ensure that errors are corrected on a timely manner, to reflect accurate balances at any given reporting period and to correctly make the necessary disclosures in the financial statements and strictly observe the proper presentation of sources of fund following as prescribed in the existing regulation;
Strictly adhere to the LDRRMF accounting guidelines provided under COA Circular No. 2012-002 and COA Circular No. 2015-009 relative to the transfer of the unexpended balance of the LDRRM Funds; and
Ensure optimum utilization of the calamity fund for expenditures that address the key objectives of disaster risk reduction and management as envisioned under R.A. No. 10121.

We reiterated our prior year’s recommendations to the management to:
Maximize the utilization of current and prior year’s appropriations of all funds earmarked for various priority programs, projects and activities. Exhaustive implementation should be undertaken by management, through extensive planning and monitoring and immediate resolution of identified issues of the remaining unimplemented 2001-2024 PPAs, to cope with the subsequent year PPA’s that equally needs prompt implementation;
Require the City Development Council and the budget committee during the preparation of the annual budget for the 20% Development Fund, GF, Economic Enterprise and SEF to include only Programs/Projects/Activities which are implementation ready and could be accomplished within the target date of completion, after taking into consideration the priorities of the LGU leadership;
Require the City Planning and Development Coordinator (CPDC) re-evaluate the programs/projects under the continuing appropriations and identify projects which are determined to still address the present development needs of the intended beneficiaries and execute them without delay, otherwise, facilitate its reversion and re-appropriation to fund other crucial development projects and programs of the city; and
Ensure that all savings from completed projects and all projects that are no longer feasible and not yet implemented are considered for immediate realignment, subject to budgetary rules, or reverted back to the unappropriated surplus for re-appropriation to other development projects.

We recommended to the management to:
Require the Offices of the City Health and City Accounting to submit immediately the noted lacking documents to substantiate the disbursed transactions;
Return the unutilized balance to DOH or seek first the authorization from the DOH if CHO-Malaybalay City choose to disburse the remaining fund. Henceforth, fast track the release and/or liquidation of future HEA benefits to maximize the utilization of the fund;
Ensure that complete supporting documents are attached as prescribed under the Memorandum of Agreement, DOH AO No. 2022-001, and DOH-DBM JAO No. 2023-001; and
Henceforth, ensure timely submission of liquidation reports to source agencies to avoid variances in records.

We recommended to the Management the following courses of action:
Provide justification on the grant of monetization despite non-adherence to the above-mentioned provisions;
Establish a policy specifically addressing the criteria and requirements for the monetization of leave credits—putting emphasis on special monetization, frequency of applying for monetization, in adherence to the guidelines outlined in Sections 22 and 23 of the CSC Omnibus Rules on Leave and CSC-DBM Joint Circular No. 2-97;
In order to verify the certification of leave credits in the application for leave form, attach a copy of the latest leave card for every application for monetization of leave credits;
Implement the CSC Resolution, in accordance with Sections 22 and 23 of the CSC Omnibus Rules on Leave, by exhausting first the balance of VL credits before SL credits;
Ensure that the reasons and the supporting documents for the request of leave credit monetization beyond 30 calendar days or 50% or more of the accumulated leave credits earned is provided, duly approved and are deemed valid and justifiable; and
Adhere to the provision that monetization of leave credits per employee shall be availed of only once a year pursuant to Section 2 of CSC-DBM Joint Circular No. 2-97.

We recommended to the Management to:
Stop the practice of advance payment for fuel, oil and lubricants;
Require the concerned offices/departments to submit a detailed explanation/ justification of all the noted deficiencies; and
Establish a sound internal control and monitoring in the utilization of fuel, oil and lubricants by strictly implementing the minimum requirements set forth under COA Circular No. 77-61, to wit:
Proper filling and approval of Driver's Trip Tickets which should be serially numbered.;
Preparation and submission of Monthly Report of Official Travels;
Proper filling, approval and control of Withdrawal Slips or Requisition and Issue Voucher which should be pre-numbered and provide the Plate number of the government vehicle, name and signature of the authorized driver, and purpose.; and
Preparation and submission of Monthly Report of Fuel Consumption of government motor transportation.

We recommended to the management to direct the City Accounting Office to:
Continue to undertake a thorough review and analysis of the details of the mandatory Inter-Agency accounts and submit to the audit team the reconciliation of amounts withheld still existing as of December 31, 2024;
Facilitate reconciliation with the concerned government agencies if necessary;
Address the bottlenecks in the delay of submission of reports to the identified government agencies to avoid recurrence in the future; and
If warranted, cause immediate remittance to various government agencies the amount due for the current and past due payables not yet remitted.

Recommendation/s:
We recommended to the management to require the:
City Accounting Office to:
Draw up a Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) to record the actual inventory cost upon re-computation of the welfare goods on hand as of December 31, 2023 thru the required weighted average method, duly supported with appropriate documents;
Consistently adopt the perpetual inventory method in recording purchases of supplies and materials for stock and record the expense only upon issuances of the same to end-users/beneficiaries;
Require from the concerned office the submission of the RSMI together with the RIS/RDS as basis for recording of the expense and reconcile regularly with the City GSO and the CSWDO Warehouse In-charge;
Maintain supplies ledger cards per item of welfare goods; and
Establish a system of reporting the issuances and distribution of goods and require regular coordination between the CSWDO Warehouse In-charge, and City GSO personnel for proper recording and correct valuation of the inventory account as at reporting date.
City General Services Office and/or City Social Welfare and Development Office to:
Maintain stock cards for welfare goods and reconcile regularly with the supplies ledger cards from the Accounting Office;
Completely and correctly fill out the RIS/RDS to facilitate reconciliation and consolidation in the RSMI;
Prepare and submit regularly and timely the RSMI together with the RIS/RDS to the City Accounting Office and reconcile accordingly; and
Physical count of welfare goods shall be undertaken regularly to detect any unaccounted items. Ensure proper storage and instruct the personnel concerned to properly organize the warehouse to hasten the inventory taking procedures at any given period.
City Social Welfare and Development Office to submit an explanation/ justification for all the noted deficiencies/ discrepancies and submit the lacking supporting documents required.

Recommendation/s:
We reiterated our recommendations to the Head of the Agency to:
Require the City Veterinary Office to
immediately conduct physical count of the biological assets and submit results thereof to the City Accounting and the City Auditor’s Office;
submit a detailed report of all the recorded biological assets listed in Annex O, which may include among others the individual animal’s status, weight, age, location and beneficiary.
Require the Appraisal Committee to determine the fair value and the cost to sell of the existing livestock and submit results of the appraisal to the City Accounting Office;
Require the City Accounting Office to effect necessary adjustments in the books of accounts after performing and conducting the proper procedures, especially in the case of biological assets which existence could no longer be traced, taking into consideration COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 and observe the appropriate measurement in accordance with IPSAS 27;
Henceforth, ensure that annual physical count of the biological assets is conducted, appraised, and necessary adjustments in the books of accounts is made.
Revisit the covenants/agreements to determine the purpose of the distributed animals for proper classification and accounting.

Recommendation/s:
We recommended the management to instruct the City Accounting Office to:
Exert more efforts to identify the Source/Donor Agencies of the balances established in CY 2007 totaling P1.125, determine the status of implementation of the said projects/programs and immediately return/revert the excess funds;
Confirm from the identified Source agencies, the balance of unliquidated fund transfers to the city as reflected in their books of accounts to facilitate reconciliation, liquidation and immediate return/reversion of excess/unused funds;
Inquire from the source agency of the awards received, about the restrictions and/or conditions for its utilization and reclassify the amount of unexpended prizes/awards, as applicable, and immediately plan the programs and activity for the said fund for immediate utilization;
Communicate or make representation with the ROD relative to the remittance of the withheld fees for its proper disposition;
Draw up a JEV to adjust the erroneous correcting entry as discussed above;
Exert effort to identify the Source agencies and purpose of unidentified subsidiary ledgers totaling P1.862 million to enable proper disposition of the balances.

Recommendation/s:
We recommended that management:
Refrain from granting full DTE on the day of return to official station and strictly observe the 50% DTE;
Strictly abide by the prescribed limit in the payment of actual hotel/lodging expenses, as provided in the EO;
Stop the payment of actual meal expenses during the travel period and limit the claim for meals only up to 30% of the DTE. Otherwise, submit legal basis for the grant in excess of the prescribed rate in the EO;
Require the concerned personnel to submit the mentioned lacking documents in Table 2 and henceforth, instruct the City Accounting Office to thoroughly review the supporting documents attached to the DVs and liquidation reports for travels to avoid the same lapses.

Recommendation/s:
We recommended to the management to direct the Accounting Office to:
Stop immediately the remittance of Pag-IBIG Fund government share in excess of the mandatory contributions;
Adhere strictly to the laws/regulations on the Pag-IBIG Fund Contributions (government share) as provided in Section 7 of RA 9679 in succeeding years;
Submit a copy of the legal basis allowing the city to increase the employer’s share to 2% of the current monthly compensation and copy of the averred SP resolution authorizing the City Mayor to match the member’s increased contribution.

We recommended to the Head of the Agency the following:
Require the City Budget Office to prepare the List of NYDDOs and other applicable reports due from the said office;
Require the City Accounting Office for timely submission of the SCBAA.

We recommended to the Head of the Agency the following:
Require the City Budget Office to ensure that the correct budgetary account is being charged for shouldering the Barangay officials and employees Philhealth Contribution. Likewise, ensure that the City’s Indigency Program budget is allocated only for the payment of PHIC premiums of qualified indigents;
Require the City Accounting Office to ensure that PHIC premium is being deducted from the wages paid to the workers who are part of the Informal Economy;
Require the City Health Office to prepare a comprehensive list of the persons enrolled in the PHIC Group Enrollment Scheme/Program, disaggregated based on employment/status classification, certified correct by the City’s HRMO. Furnish the same to the City Accounting and Budget Office.

We recommended to the Management the following:
Strictly adhere and comply with the existing guidelines in the proper recording of loyalty Incentives;
Provide written valid justification of the inconsistencies and irregularities in the procurement of gold rings incentives instead of silver rings which is inconsistent with its approved PRAISE, otherwise said payment shall be disallowed in audit;
Justify variances noted in the list of recipients of gold ring incentives and provide a list of recipients of gold-plated loyalty pins, otherwise, said portion shall be disallowed in audit; and
Henceforth, abide by the approved PRAISE and corresponding CSC Memorandum and adhere to the principle of providing incentives and awards at par with the actual performance/service rendered by the employee(s).

We recommended to the Head of the Agency to:
Instruct the CAO to update and enhance the internal audit system of the City, being the Office mandated by RA 7160 to take charge thereof;
Instruct the BAC to devise an comprehensive internal guidelines on the entitlement of BAC honorarium, circumscribed by applicable rules and regulations prescribed by DBM;
Copy furnish the COA with the approved internal control policy and guidelines;
Determine and refund the amount of overpayment.

We recommended to the Head of the Agency to:
Examine if the remaining balance of trust fund accounts are actually LGU equity share, and if deemed warranted, require the reversion of which to the General Fund. Otherwise, return the unexpended balance to its source agency;
Require the City Accountant and City Treasurer to consider closing the bank accounts subject herein, locate the supporting documents, and prepare the necessary adjusting entries;
Perform the appropriate procedures to expedite the immediate destruction or return of the obsolete checks to the bank in order to eliminate accountability of the accountable officer over the checks which are no longer needed in the operations of the city government; and
Henceforth, annually evaluate the bank accounts to ensure that all inactive bank accounts are closed

We recommended to the management the following:
